nager%20and%20TTable.%20TransactionManager%20handles%20all%20control%20operations%20(begin(),%20commit(),%20and%20abort())%20on%20behalf%20of%20the%20application.%20In%20this%20context,%20TransactionManager.begin()%20returns%20a%20unique%20transaction%20id%20(txid),%20to%20be%20used%20in%20subsequent%20calls.%20TTable%20is%20a%20transactional%20equivalent%20of%20HBase%E2%80%99s%20HTable.%20It%20augments%20HTable%E2%80%99s%20data%20access%20methods%20(get(),%20scan(),%20put(),%20and%20delete())%20with%20the%20txid%20parameter,%20to%20convey%20the%20transaction%E2%80%99s%20context.%20%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20following%20example%20demonstrates%20how%20to%20use%20Omid%E2%80%99s%20transactional%20API%20to%20modify%20two%20rows%20in%20an%20HBase%20table%20with%20ACID%20guarantees,%20which%20it%E2%80%99s%20not%20possible%20with%20the%20standard%20HBase%20API.%20We%20assume%20prior%20HBase%20programming%20experience.%20For%20background,%20please%20see%20the%20%3Ca%20href=%22http://hbase.apache.org/book.html%22%20target=%22_blank%22%3EHBase%20programming%20manual%3C/a%3E.%20%3Cbr/%3E%3C/p%3E%3Cblockquote%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EOmid%20Code%20Example%3C/b%3E%3Ci%3E%3Cbr/%3E%3C/i%3E%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3EConfiguration%20conf%20=%20HBaseConfiguration.create();%3Cbr/%3ETransactionManager%20tm%20=%20HBaseTransactionManager.newBuilder()%3Cbr/%3E%20%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0.withConfiguration(conf)%3Cbr/%3E%20%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0%C2%A0.build();%3Cbr/%3ETTable%20tt%20=%20new%20TTable(conf,%20&ldquo;EXAMPLE_TABLE&rdquo;);%3Cbr/%3E%3Cbr/%3Ebyte[]%20family%20=%20Bytes.toBytes(&ldquo;EXAMPLE_CF&rdquo;);%3Cbr/%3Ebyte[]%20qualifier%20=%20Bytes.toBytes(&ldquo;EXAMPLE_QUAL&rdquo;);%3Cbr/%3E%3Cbr/%3ETransaction%20tx%20=%20tm.begin();%3Cbr/%3EPut%20row1%20=%20new%20Put(Bytes.toBytes(&ldquo;EXAMPLE_ROW1&rdquo;));%3Cbr/%3Erow1.add(family,%20qualifier,%20Bytes.toBytes(&ldquo;VALUE_1&rdquo;));%3Cbr/%3Ett.put(tx,%20row1);%3Cbr/%3EPut%20row2%20=%20new%20Put(Bytes.toBytes(&ldquo;EXAMPLE_ROW2&rdquo;));%3Cbr/%3Erow2.add(family,%20qualifier,%20Bytes.toBytes(&ldquo;VALUE_2&rdquo;));%3Cbr/%3Ett.put(tx,%20row2);%3Cbr/%3Etm.commit(tx);%3Cbr/%3E%3Cbr/%3Ett.close();%3Cbr/%3Etm.close();%3C/i%3E%3C/p%3E%3C/blockquote%3E%3Cp%3EPlease%20refer%20to%20this%20github%20%3Ca%20href=%22https://github.com/yahoo/omid/wiki/Basic-Examples%22%20target=%22_blank%22%3Epage%20%3C/a%3Efor%20more%20code%20examples.%C2%A0%20%3Cb%3E%3Cbr/%3E%3C/b%3E%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3E%3Cbr/%3E%3C/b%3E%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cb%3EA%20Case%20for%20Snapshot%20Isolation%3C/b%3E%3Cbr/%3E%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20%E2%80%9CI%E2%80%9D%20in%20ACID%20is%20for%20Isolation%20-%20preventing%20concurrently%20executing%20transactions%20from%20seeing%20each%20other%E2%80%99s%20partial%20updates.%20The%20isolation%20property%20is%20essential%20for%20consistency.%20Informally,%20it%20ensures%20that%20the%20information%20a%20transaction%20reads%20from%20the%20database%20%E2%80%9Cmakes%20sense%E2%80%9D%20in%20that%20it%20does%20not%20mix%20old%20and%20new%20values.%20For%20example,%20if%20a%20Sieve%20transaction%20updates%20the%20reverse-anchortext%20feature%20of%20multiple%20pages%20linked-to%20by%20the%20page%20being%20processed,%20then%20no%20concurrent%20transaction%20may%20observe%20the%20old%20value%20of%20that%20%C2%A0feature%20for%20some%20of%20these%20pages%20and%20the%20new%20value%20for%20the%20rest.%20%3Cbr/%3E%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3EMore%20formally,%20a%20system%20satisfies%20a%20consistency%20model%20if%20every%20externally%20observable%20execution%20hi 20quest%20for%20models%20that%20translate%20to%20scalable%20implementations.%C2%A0%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3EA%20%3Ca%20href=%22http://research.microsoft.com/apps/pubs/default.aspx?id=69541%22%20target=%22_blank%22%3Eseminal%20paper%20by%20Bernstein%20et%20al.%3C/a%3E%20suggested%20a%20new%20model,%20named%20Snapshot%20Isolation%20(SI),%20which%20relaxes%20the%20correctness%20criteria%20of%20serializability%20&ndash;%20most%20applications%20do%20not%20require%20such%20a%20strict%20correctness%20criteria%20&ndash;%20and%20it%20is%20suitable%20for%20lock-free%20implementations.%20In%20a%20nutshell,%20SI%20allows%20transactions%20to%20be%20reduced%20to%20two%20points%20instead%20of%20one:%20a%20reading%20point%20and%20a%20writing%20point.%20Inconsistent%20reads%20do%20not%20occur,%20since%20each%20transaction%20sees%20a%20consistent%20snapshot%20of%20the%20database.%20This%20means%20that%20for%20two%20concurrent%20transactions%20T1%20and%20T2,%20T1%20sees%20either%20all%20of%20T2%E2%80%99s%20updates%20to%20data%20items%20it%20is%20reading,%20or%20none%20of%20T2%E2%80%99s%20updates.%20SI%20guarantees%20that%20(1)%20all%20reads%20in%20a%20transaction%20see%20a%20consistent%20snapshot%20of%20the%20database,%20and%20(2)%20a%20transaction%20successfully%20commits%20only%20if%20no%20update%20it%20has%20made%20conflicts%20with%20any%20concurrent%20updates%20made%20since%20that%20snapshot.%20As%20stated%20before,%20while%20SI%20is%20slightly%20different%20from%20serializability%20in%20terms%20of%20correctness%20(e.g.%20SI%20does%20not%20avoid%20the%20write-skew%20anomaly),%20SI%20implementations%20offer%20a%20better%20performance%20than%20strict%20serializability%20implementations.%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20diagram%20below%20illustrates%20snapshot%20isolation.%20In%20simple%20terms,%20two%20transactions%20conflict%20under%20SI%20if%20and%20only%20if:%201)%20they%20execute%20concurrently%20(overlap%20in%20time);%20and%202)%20write%20to%20the%20same%20element%20of%20a%20particular%20row%20(spatial%20overlap).%20Here,%20transactions%20T1%20and%20T2%20overlap%20in%20time%20but%20not%20in%20space%20(their%20write%20sets%20do%20not%20contain%20modifications%20on%20the%20same%20items),%20therefore%20they%20can%20both%20commit.%20T2%20and%20T3%20overlap%20in%20time%20and%20in%20space%20(both%20write%20to%20R4),%20therefore%20one%20of%20them%20must%20be%20aborted%20to%20avoid%20consistency%20violation.%20T4%20on%20the%20other%20hand,%20does%20not%20overlap%20any%20other%20transaction%20in%20time%20and%20can%20therefore%20commit.%3C/p%3E%3Cfigure%20class=%22tmblr-full%22%20data-orig-height=%22305%22%20data-orig-width=%22720%22%3E%3Cimg%20data-orig-height=%22305%22%20data-orig-width=%22720%22%20alt=%22image%22%20src=%22https://66.media.tumblr.com/ee6ee99354e0ef5e89ccf1eb42a7e9cc/tumblr_inline_nuj98tx4G91t17fny_540.jpg%22/%3E%3C/figure%3E%3Cp%3ESnapshot%20isolation%20is%20amenable%20to%20scalable%20implementations.%20NoSQL%20datastores%20that%20support%20multi-version%20concurrency%20control%20(MVCC),%20namely%20storing%20multiple%20versions%20capturing%20the%20history%20of%20an%20item%20associated%20with%20a%20unique%20key,%20are%20suitable%20for%20implementing%20SI.%20In%20such%20a%20system,%20transactions%20read%20data%20via%20immutable%20snapshots%20based%20on%20historic%20versions,%20and%20write%20data%20by%20creating%20new%20versions.%20Therefore,%20reads%20and%20writes%20need%20no%20coordination.%20Furthermore,%20writes%20can%20proceed%20without%20coordinating%20with%20concurrent%20transactions%20until%20they%20attempt%20to%20commit,%20at%20which%20time%20inter-transaction%20order%20is%20established%20and%20conflicts%20are%20detected.%3C/p%3E%3Cp%3EFortunately,%20HBase%20is%20natively%20multi-versioned,%20whereby%20clients%20can%20control%20version%20numbers%20(timestamps)%20and%20retrieve%20data%20through%20snapshots%20associated%20with%20a%20given%20timestamp.%20While%20this%20API%20is%20complex%20to%20use%20in%20regular%20applications,%20it%20is%20a%20perfe
